But here, reader, before we proceed to the trials of these offenders, we shall, after we usual manner, premise some things which it may be necessary for thee to know.
It hath been observed, I think, by many, as well as the celebrated writer of three letters, that no human institution is capable of consummate perfection.
An observation which, perhaps, that writer at least gathered from discovering some defects in the polity even of this well-regulated nation.
And, indeed, if there should be any such defect in a constitution which my Lord Coke long ago told us “the wisdom of all the wise men in the world, if all the wise men in the world had all met together at one time, could not have equalled,” which some of our wisest men who were met together long before said was too good to be altered in any particular, and which, nevertheless, hath been mending ever since, by a very great number of the said wise men: if, I say, this constitution should be imperfect, us may be allowed, I think, to doubt whether any such faultless model can be found among the institutions of men.
